PG| ***** 47 ***** |


AT|   I'd say: YES.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


ht|c|cs|6|at|^B@2 {  Is it on after a Double or Overcall?  }|
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


AT|    I'd say: NO.|
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


ht|e|cs|6|at|^B@2 {  How high is the partnership forced after the raise from 1 to 2?  }|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


va|2|AT|
I recommend that you can stop in a partscore if either player's next bid is 2NT or 3-of-the-minor. Otherwise, it is Game Forcing.|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


ht|h|cs|6|at|^B@2 {  How light can the raise from 1 to 3 be?  }|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


va|2|AT|
I suggest relying on the vulnerability. At favorable, it can be something like Jxxxxx and out. At unfavorable, it would be much sounder, maybe up to AQ10xxx and out.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


ht|k|cs|6|at|^B@2 {  How many cards to raise?  }|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


va|2|AT|
In clubs, usually five or more. In diamonds, five are also the normal requirement, but it can occasionally be done with four (since a one-diamond opener is usually four-plus cards).|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


ht|n|cs|6|at|^B@2 {  What does it mean if opener bids 2-of-a-Major after an inverted raise?  }|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


va|2|AT|
I recommend that it show a stopper/concentration (it is pointless to show a 4-card major, since responder should never raise a minor with a 4-card major). After this show of concentration, if responder bids 2NT or 3-of-the-minor, it can be passed.|
